The former Gozo ferry Xlendi was scuttled off Xatt l-Aħmar in Gozo on November 12, 1999 in order to become a diving attraction.

The ship was built in 1955 as a train ferry in Scandinavia and bought by Gozo Chanel in 1990.

It was used mainly for cargo services between Sa' Maison and Mġarr harbour but was decommissioned in 1997.
Today's front page #TimesofMalta

#TimesGoneBy:  The Gozo ferry 'Għawdex'

The Gozo Channel ferry 'Għawdex' preparing to berth at Ċirkewwa in 1996. Built in Bremen in 1962, it was bought by the Maltese government in 1978 and was in service until the end of the 1990s. It was then sold to Portuguese shipowners but was laid up in Malta until it was sold for breaking up in Turkey in 2002. 

The ferry was the biggest to operate between Malta and Gozo but  was considered impractical because its bow and stern doors were too small for container trucks. The large funnel was a fake, put up for appearance's sake.

#TimesGoneBy: Youths protest against violence and biased broadcasting, December 30, 1984

Several hundred young people held a protest march from St Aloysius College to the gates of the President's Palace in Attard to protest over political violence and biased broadcasting.

 A donation of cash and toys to local charities and Ethiopian famine victims was presented to President Agatha Barbara, but the President appeared to be offended by the contents of a letter which was also handed to her, insisting she would not let anyone involve her in partisan politics. 

She handed the letter back to one of the youths and was then seen approaching a section of the crowd before being calmed down by the police, who intervened to escort her out of the crowd.

The youths then started singing the national anthem and were dispersed by the police while the President  rebuked one of the organisers who had invited her to speak to the crowd.

Events such as this were organised by the group known as Tan-numri, one of whose leaders was Joe (Peppi) Azzopardi.

#TimesGoneBy: Cars drive into Kingsgate

Cars are seen being driven through Kingsgate, or Porta Reale, in this late 1950s picture of what later became more commonly known as City Gate in Valletta. This gate – the third for Valletta's main entrance – was built in 1853 to designs by Lieutenant-Colonel Francis Ringler Thomson.  

Two statues were placed on either side of the arches, one of Philippe Villiers de L'Isle-Adam, the first Grand Master in Malta, and one of Jean Parisot de Valette, the founder of the city. A bronze bust of Pope Pius V, who made significant financial contributions to the building of Valletta, was placed above the archway looking into Strada Reale (Republic Street) in 1892.

The gate was demolished in the summer of 1964 to be replaced by an Italian modernist design by Alziro Bergonzo, which was also demolished and replaced by a Renzo Piano design in 2011.

#TimesGoneBy: Star of Malta capsizes, July 29, 1955

Star of Malta ran aground in thick early mist on the Mercanti Reef some 200 feet off Dragonara Point and capsized. The ship was carrying 57 passengers. Some were on deck at the time while others were preparing to go to breakfast. Some passengers and crew swam ashore or were picked up by a fleet of small boats which came to their assistance.

#TimesGoneBy: University students' demonstration, April 24 1985.

University students expressed their solidarity with applicants who were refused admission to the University, despite having the required academic qualifications. 

In the protest, the participating students wore black as a symbolic sign of mourning. In 1985 only 236 students were admitted to the university. 

During the demonstration, the students held streamers saying "The control of minds: a repressive weapon" and "Dictators cherish ignorance". Some carried Maltese flags with a black ribbon, as a sign of mourning, others carried placards. 

The protest ended at the University library, where the students lay on the ground as if they were dead.

#TimesGoneBy: Hijacked KLM plane lands in Luqa, November 26, 1973.

A hijacked KLM Boeing 747 landed in Luqa airport, the first time a jumbo jet had landed on Maltese islands. 

The aircraft had been flying from Amsterdam to Tokyo with a stop in Beirut. It was hijacked over Iraq early in the morning and landed in Malta without permission after it was refused landing permission elsewhere.

After tense negotiations between the Palestinian gunmen and Prime Minister Dom Mintoff, 225 passengers on aboard were released. Mintoff had refused to refuel the aircraft unless the passengers were released.

The passengers, mostly Japanese, were released during the night between November 26-27 - coming down chutes from the plane as the aircraft stairs available in Malta were unsuitable for a Boeing 747.

The hijackers asked for an Egyptian consul to replace the passengers as a hostage, but the KLM senior vice president for operations, A.W. Witholt, offered himself as hostage and was allowed on the aircraft.

Mr Mintoff was later praised for the tough way he had negotiated with the hijackers. At one point, after the hijackers had agreed to release the passengers, he also requested the release of the air hostesses.

He was heard on the radio telling the hijackers that the hostesses were only of use to them to make tea.

He also told them that he had spoken to Libyan leader Muammar Gaddafi, who told him they did not represent anyone and were just young people acting on their own.

"You have no friends, and I am your only friend at the moment. I am trying to help you out but now I am determined to help you only as much as you help me," Mr Mintoff was heard to say on two-way radios.

At this juncture, an interpreter told Mr Mintoff that he would not repeat certain words he had told the hijackers because he feared the gunmen would get furious.

The gunmen got furious when Col Gaddafi was mentioned. They said the Libyans had treated them badly "not like you."

Eventually the hijackers relented, telling Mr Mintoff that in view of his invaluable help, they were overlooking everything, including their instructions not to release the hostesses, and they were also allowed to disembark. 

The plane then took off and the drama later ended peacefully in Dubai.

#TimesGoneBy: The Labour Cabinet: December 20, 1981

President Anton Buttigieg swore in the new Labour government ministers after the general election of December 1981. It was a controversial general election, in which the Labour Party won a majority of seats in parliament despite winning a minority of votes.

The President is seen sixth from right with (from left) Lino Spiteri, Karmenu Vella, Joe Grima, Reno Calleja, Philip Muscat, Lorry Sant, Guze' Cassar, Alex Sceberras Trigona, Freddie Micallef,  Wistin Abela, Patrick Holland, Danny Cremona and Censu Moran. Only five survive and only one is still in public office – Karmenu Vella (second from left) is today EU commissioner for the environment.

#TimesGoneBy: Hal Dghejf fireworks explosion, March 12, 2008

As Malta was swearing in its new Cabinet, the island was rattled by a powerful fireworks explosion in a garage in Naxxar. 

The blast killed a young mother-of-two and a 47-year-old man and brought down three houses. 

A lucky survivor, Rachel Bugeja, was inside one of the three houses that were destroyed by the explosion. She was asleep in her bedroom but was saved by a wardrobe that fell over her bed, shielding her from the falling ceiling.

Waiting for Mintoff at the airport

Crowd wait for Prime Minister Dom Mintoff at the old airport arrivals terminal in Luqa in 1972. He was returning from Rome where he held tense talks with UK and Nato officials about the use of British military bases here. He initially gave the British forces a deadline to withdraw but then negotiated a settlement which extended the use of the bases to 1979. The talks were given global coverage. The Chicago Tribune reported on January 16, 1972 how Mr Mintoff was given a 'wild homecoming' by a 'frenzied crowd of thousands of chanting and screaming Maltese'.
Picture above crowds hailing him as a 'saviour' of Malta while the newspaper said he was proclaimed 'a saint' by frenzied fans.

The June issue of Pink, Malta's magazine for women out with today's The Sunday Times of Malta, has a strong fashion dimension once again, crossing over into the arts scene and bringing the two worlds together.

Apart from showcasing the upcoming summer trends, it features designers who hand-paint and customise shoes and exquisite haute couture collections that resemble works of art, as well as relives The Pink Fashion Show on film and spots the top looks off the catwalk.

Art also takes centre stage with the abstract works of up-and-coming artists, while dance whirls its way into the magazine, discussing the position of female choreographers in a man's world, and its far-reaching beneficial effects on persons with disability, who are finding their showbiz feet.

Apart from its fashion strength, Pink also flexes its muscles in the beauty, health and fitness departments, with a good dose of food, humour and history, always from a female point of view.

A monthly magazine, Pink is produced and published by Allied Newspapers Ltd and printed by Progress Press.

Places magazine out tomorrow

Take a stroll down St Ursula Street in Valletta via Places: Design & Living magazine tomorrow and discover its regeneration into a road of boutique hotels, artists' studios, renovations and roof gardens with superb harbour views.

The May issue of the magazine, out with The Sunday Times of Malta tomorrow, also peers into a neo-futuristic fifth-floor penthouse and takes a look at mirrors, both antique and contemporary, to outline their restoration process and show what's available today.

Places also reflects on a variety of workspaces, from those of a religious nature to designer studios – far from the classic image of the messy, paint-splattered studio – and a self-contained, purpose-built residency unit for artists to be inspired.

Tomorrow's issue of the bimonthly magazine, published and produced by Allied Newspapers Ltd and printed by Progress Press, also takes readers on a tour through Milan Design Week, capturing the highlights as seen through the eyes of photographer and architecture student Sean Mallia.

Government massively exceeding its own wage bill projections - de Marco

Government spending on civil service pay by the end of this year would be €80 million more than it had itself projected, reflecting its incompetence, the Shadow Minister of Finance, Mario de Marco, told parliament this evening.

Speaking in parliament during the Budget debate on the Ministry of Finance, Dr de Marco also observed that in the first two years of this government, recurrent expenditure had increased by 22 per cent, twice the increase in the whole of the last legislature.

It was no wonder, he noted, that credit rating agencies had said that the sharp growth in the civil service could be an issue of concern if the economy did not maintain its growth.

The current economic growth momentum, he said, did not start with this government but under the previous one. The Maltese economy performed better than the EU even during the worst of the international financial crisis.
 
Under the present government, the civil service wage bill – excluding para-statal agencies – had grown sharply - from €612million in 2012 to €790 million. Most of this increase was due to the exaggerated public service recruitment in areas where it was not needed.  

Spending on wages as a percentage of GDP had risen to 9.2 per cent compared to a peak of 8.8 per cent under the former government in 2009. At that time the increase was not because of civil service recruitment but a slowdown in the economy caused by the international financial crisis.   

Public sector consumption now formed a much bigger part of GDP than ever before and was growing faster than the private  sector. 

Dr de Marco also noted that Malta's deficit would have been far wider had the government not received overdue social security contributions from Enemalta. That meant that the government had sold a capital asset and used the funds for its recurrent spending

Under this government, debt had also increased by €600 million, or €25,000 an hour, and Malta had nothing to show for it. The government was even failing to identify new growth areas for the economy.

In his speech Dr de Marco underscored the need for action to improve Malta's economic competitiveness. He stressed that keeping fuel prices high, as the present government was doing, would undermine competitiveness. 

He also spoke on the distribution of wealth and said the number of people at risk of poverty or in poverty had actually increased under the present government.

"The government is interested in headlines more than the poverty line," Dr de Marco said. 

He also expressed concern on the level of adequacy of pensions. Measures taken by the government to boost third pillar pensions had not worked, he said. Furthermore he was advocating discussion on possible introduction of second pillar pensions.  He was not saying second pillar pensions should be introduced,but a discussion needed to be held, he said.

Breaking news, breaking boundaries for 80 years

Two events at the beginning of August 1935 bore all the hallmarks of the turmoil and carnage that was to tear Europe apart in a bloody war.

On August 7, 1935, 60 per cent of voters in Gdansk, Poland, agreed to Nazism. Just four days later, a mass Nazi demonstration against German Jews was held.

For Anne Rossi, 92, World War II turned out to be a highly interesting period in her life because it enabled her to put her talents to good use – helping defend the island against the attackers from the air.

In the early 1940s, Ms Rossi worked as a plotter at the Lascaris War Rooms, the underground secret complex located more than 120 metres below the Upper Barrakka Gardens. It served as Britain's war headquarters in Malta.

"I met all the high-ranking officers of the time," the great-great-grandmother of three recalled. "I believe Timber Woods used to live next to Hastings and he had a girlfriend, who was a foreigner. My job brought me into contact with many high-ranking officers, as did my father." Ms Rossi's father, Ernest Mallia, was the only Maltese squadron leader and was honoured with an OBE by King George VI himself in 1944.

For full coverage on the #CharlieHebdo incident, read today's paper or visit www.timesofmalta.com

#Journalism has the ability to shed light on people's struggles with life and bring their stories to the attention of generous readers who can help. Such was the case of Javier Micallef, pictured here with his parents. The seven-year-old, who was born without a large portion of his brain, was able to receive three weeks of intensive therapy in a specialised clinic in York thanks to the generosity of The Sunday Times of Malta readers. 

To find out more of Javier's story and others who were helped in 2014, read today's paper or visit www.timesofmalta.com

Solo parenting is no mean feat and Pink magazine, out with The Sunday Times of Malta tomorrow, delves into what it takes to bring up children alone, while not scrounging off the State.

Mothers from around the world talk about how they are coping with raising children while being the #breadwinners too.

The monthly women's magazine also follows up the #Soroptimist International public forum on ending sexual violence in conflict, focusing on children born from #violence and rape in war, who fall in the gap between their victim mother and abuser father.

And here is Sonya's poem! 

The Aya Sofya, majestic and fine -
Its glittering mosaics are so divine,

The Topkapi Palace, with its Turkish Bath
And courtyards and kiosks and the Harem path,

The steamy bathhouses and massage rooms,
Stupendous domes and Royalty Tombs,

The Blue Mosque with six minarets, Iznic tiles,
The various museums depicting all styles

Of great architecture that came with the years -
A history of battles won amongst such fears ...

The Galata Tower there in Beyoğlu.
Stands high o'er the city and beckons to you -

The view is breathtaking - the city below
Is unique in all ways, wherever you go....

The Bosphorous shimmers, its waters so clear -
The beauty around you's more than you can bear.  

All this makes Istanbul a real special place
That memories remain in your heart, always .........

You don't have to be David Beckham to be a hero to your kids.

It's Fathers' Day on Sunday and timesofmalta.com is making an appeal to readers who would like to nominate their father, stepfather, grandfather or even great grandfather as the best dad ever.

status_message:
Man seriously injured in Zejtun crash

An elderly man was seriously injured in a crash at Tal-Barrani road this morning.

The crash took place at the intersection to Zejtun at about 7.30 a.m. The traffic lights were reportedly off at the time.

The crash involved a VW Golf driven by a 48-year-old from Marsa heading towards Birzebbuga and a green Maruti 800 driven by a 75-year-old from Zejtun.

The Maruti, which was crossing the road towards Zejtun, was overturned and pushed into a wall with the force of impact. The driver was trapped in his vehicle and was rescued by Civil Protection rescuers using cutting equipment.

The driver of the other vehicle was not hurt, but both vehicles were extensively damaged.

The south-bound carriageway of Tal-Barrani road is closed.

status_message:
Muscat: We are humbled by the result

Labour leader Joseph Muscat said this afternoon that he was humbled by the huge Labour Party victory at the polls.

In comments to PBS, Dr Muscat said he wanted to promise a government which would be close to the people. "What the people give you in one day, they can take away in another day," he said.

He said that the new Labour government would seek to work with the opposition and live true to its promise of giving a Malta for all Maltese

Franco Debono celebrates with Labour

Former PN MP Franco Debono was seen celebrating the Labour victory this afternoon.

Last December he voted against the government in the Budget vote, causing the government's collapse.

timesofmalta.com is currently down, follow us here on facebook

Please share

Labour wins huge victory


The Labour Party has won a huge general election victory, sweeping to power with a majority of 55% or some 20,000 votes.
The party is expected to have a parliamentary majority of between five and seven seats.
Supporters are pouring into the streets in celebration heading towards Labour headquarters in Hamrun, honking their horns and waving white Labour flags as well as some of the old red ones.
This is Labour;s first Labour victory in 16 years and its biggest since the immediate post-war era.
Prime Minister Lawrence Gonzi conceded defeat after the first sample as the sorting of ballot papers started. He phoned Joseph Muscat to congratulate him.
In the Naxxar counting hall there were scenes of jubilation as Labour party agents hugged each other with tears in their eyes.
Fireworks were let off in some localities
Optimism and enthusiasm had been building early in the Labour ranks as opinion polls showed their party consistently in the lead and as vote turnout figures last night showed an appreciable drop only in the PN-leaning districts.
Small crowds started gathering in mid-morning outside PL headquarters and in various squares.
In Cospicua, a man said (at 10 a.m.) that he was sure Labour would win, but, he said, they were holding off celebrations for now because of what happened five years ago (when celebrations were short lived because it was the PN which actually won)
"Even Bormlizi who never voted, not even for Mintoff, came out to vote yesterday," one elderly man said.
Another man said that five years ago he was celebrating with PN but now he felt that he was in the right place celebrating with Labour

 A front-page picture carried in The Times today as well as video footage carried yesterday has raised a wave of anger on the social media, with people voicing consternation over the attire of the accused, as well as their attitude.

The five were seen entering the law courts building in the afternoon wearing shorts and T-shirts and carrying soft drink bottles. They were taken to court in a police van, more than 24-hours after a brawl at Il-Maghluq, Marsaxlokk, where a man was assaulted during a protest over illegal camping.

Some of the arraigned were wearing the same clothes they had worn at the beach.

A number of people entering the law courts to follow proceedings were also seen wearing shorts.

The norm is for smart clothes, including jacket and tie.

Many writing on the social media also complained about the sentence meted out by the court after the accused pleaded guilty - a fine of €60 each. One of the accused admitted committing a crime during the operative period of a suspended sentence and had his term extended by two years.

The following are some comments seen on facebook:

"Sadly the photograph on the front page of today's printed Times is not (yet) reproduced online which is a pity as it shows the Famous Five after they were fined €60 each. Naturally Perhaps one of the many avvocati, avvocatini, avvocatoni or avvocatucci that exist within this hallowed Republic can explain to me what "suspended sentence" really means! From what I garnered up to now, it means getting away with what you've done and then being allowed to take part in at least one brawl! Fair enough"...

Continue reading:
http://www.timesofmalta.com/articles/view/20120814/local/picture-draws-angry-reaction.432852

status_message: TIMES OF MALTA WOULD LIKE TO WISH YOU ALL A MERRY CHRISTMAS

A very happy Christmas to all readers. 

The Times will not be published on Monday, Boxing Day, and will be back on the news stands on Tuesday. The Sunday Times will be out tomorrow, Christmas Day. 

Picture shows a detail from Fr Edgar Vella's Neapolitan crib. 
Photo: Jason Borg

Pink December issue out tomorrow

Should teens have technology in their bedrooms? Pink asks their mothers. How demeaning have adverts been towards females? The magazine chronicles publicity through the ages.

Why do some women shun Christmas? It gets to the heart of the matter in tomorrow's December issue, out with The Times tomorrow.

Fashion also takes pride of place with pages of accessories, trends and top gifts; as well as encounters with style gurus, insight into luxurious fragrances and a 16-page catalogue of Gaba jewellery for readers to find their choice gems at their fingertips.

But the upcoming festive season also seeps into the magazine, which profiles the standard – and dysfunctional – family lunch on Christmas Day, and offers guidelines on how to ensure it turns out to be a peaceful and sane event.

From the health point of view, the problems of sufferers of eating disorders are aggravated over this period as they have to face forced feeding at family gatherings and shopping for party dresses that tends to hammer their problems home.

The December issue also contains its fair share of history, humour, horoscopes and home décor, which focuses on Christmas crafts on a budget, but an abundance of creativity.

It also includes its usual fix of fitness, books, cookery and the best parties so far in the build-up to the festive season.

Pink is a monthly magazine, published by Allied Newspapers Ltd, printed by Progress Press and produced by Mediamaker

status_message:
Santa is a fraud!

Mothers looking to create a better balance between career and family will pick up a few tips from one woman who has turned it into a fine art and writes about her experience in the latest issue of Child out tomorrow free with The Times.

The magazine for parents takes its mission seriously, featuring several other articles with information that help readers make important decisions about bringing up their children. They range from insights into handling difficult teenagers to the importance of avoiding fights in front of the kids; the supporting role fathers can have for new mothers to keeping the peace in the family during Christmas.

Speaking of Christmas, interviews with children who've dumped the Santa Claus myth makes for entertaining reading, as do readers' anecdotes about the funniest things their child has ever told them.

And don't let your son or daughter lose out on an opportunity to take part in a fabulous competition – they can win backstage passes to this year's panto at the Manoel Theatre!
Watch out for Pink tomorrow, out with The Times!

- Men magazine out tomorrow with The Times -

To be strong at 20 is expected – your body is still quite new and the genes are on your side. To be strong at 50 may require some maintenance but it's doable. But to be strong at 80 is no mean feat.

In M magazine, out tomorrow with The Times, George Cini meets Joe "Powerful" Falzon, a former strongman who, among other feats, managed to pull a Boeing 727 aircraft for 30 feet, push a 21-ton train, bend metal rods, crush stones and sleep on broken glass. He may now be 80 years old but he is still a force to be reckoned with.

In another life-affirming interview, M meets Captain Tom Harris who, in 2009, lost a leg in an explosion in Afghanistan. But that did not stop him from co-founding the Race2Recovery team with other amputees to raise money for charity. The team is planning to be the first amputees to race in the Dakar Rally.
M also takes a look at Marquis Nicholas de Piro's photo album, interviews world-acclaimed photographer Stanislas Guigui and goes on stage with actor Alan Montanaro and his wife Gaby.

M magazine is designed by MediaMaker Limited and printed by Progress Press Limited, both members of the Allied Group. Its editor is Stanley Borg.

status_message: Out today! Grab your copy!
Pink Magazine out tomorrow!

My daughter in darkness

A 20-year-old mother, who was reduced to a vegetative state in a motorbike accident a year ago, has finally left hospital – despite her family being told she would be confined to a home for the elderly for life.

But Anna Bajada is as much a fighter as her daughter Angie, and apart from raising the rest of her family and her two-year-old granddaughter, she is making sure to improve the quality of life of her semi-conscious child.

Pink catches up with the three generations to see how hope is propelling them through the ordeal of coping with a daughter they can barely communicate with, and feeds directly through a hole in her belly, despite the frustrating fact that she can smell, taste and loves her food.

In tomorrow's issue of the magazine, Pink also gets to know a 60-year-old grandmother and her motives behind placing a personal advert to find a husband.

It also signs up to the social networking site Badoo to understand the way the virtual clubbing scene has been brought into the bedroom and the changing face of dating, highlighting that the art of chatting up has taken on a whole new dimension.

Before Dr John Briffa, a specialist in nutrition and weight loss, renowned in the UK, launches his latest book on escaping the diet trap in January, he has chosen Malta as the first place to reveal the ground-breaking concepts contained in it.
In Pink's fitness pages, he turns the tables on conventional dieting, binning the typical calorie counting, portion control… and consequent hunger.

Pink is a monthly magazine, published by Allied Newspapers Ltd, printed by Progress Press and produced by Mediamaker.

status_message:
AFM magazine today, open day tomorrow

The sixth issue of On Parade, the annual publication of the Armed Forces of Malta, will be distributed with The Times today on the eve of the army's Open Day.

This publication offers an insight into the operations Maltese troops are involved in, particularly overseas, as well as soldiers' training, new equipment acquisitions, overhauls and EU-funded projects.

Sunday's AFM's Open Day will be held at Luqa Barracks from 10 a.m. This all-day family event will showcase varied skills and work performed by army units.

These include dynamic displays, aerial ropeways, helicopter demonstrations, abseiling and unarmed combat. The newly acquired Air Wing's Maritime Patrol Aircraft King Air will perform a flypast.

A weapons stand, scale models and other static display stands, assets and capabilities will be set up around the barracks and personnel will be providing detailed explanations to the public. Refreshments, warm meals and a children's play area will be available. The day will be capped with a Changing of the Guard ceremony and Beating the Retreat by the AFM Band at 6 p.m.

On Parade is designed by Mediamaker Ltd and printed by Progress Press, both members of the Allied Group of Companies. It is edited by the Headquarters AFM's Public Information Cell.

status_message:
Four cover versions of Pink

The multifaceted September issue of Pink magazine will be available in four different covers tomorrow, so readers can take their pick or collect all the versions.

It is the last edition to be produced in the present format before it is resized to more manageable dimensions next month, in keeping with market preferences, while continuing with its usual level of content and dose of regulars.

From one inspirational man and his handling of imminent death to another extra/ordinary woman, championing animal welfare by chance, the magazine, distributed with The Times, profiles individuals who have a singular tale to tell.

Three creative ladies string together more than just a couple of sentences in FashionStory, crafting their own bespoke jewellery and the upcoming trends of the autumn/winter season show that history repeats itself even in terms of fashion.

The rest of Pink is replete with culture, cuisine, books, beauty, fitness and fun, humour and horoscopes, health and those who live a holistic lifestyle, psychology and events.

Published by Allied Newspapers Ltd and printed by Progress Press, Pink is produced by Mediamaker. Its executive editor is Fiona Galea Debono and it is designed by Helen Cassar Torreggiani and Manuel Schembri.

status_message:
Where were you on 9/11?


Few people will forget the surreal moment ten years ago when they saw planes smashing into New York's iconic Twin Towers.

The horrific attacks, which unfolded live on millions of TV screens, left 3,000 people dead and the rest of the world stunned.
As part of an anniversary feature for September 11th, timesofmalta.com is inviting readers to send in their comments and experiences.

Where were you when you heard the news? How did you react? Were you worried for family or friends? Were you about to catch a plane and had second thoughts?  Did you happen to be close to New York at the time? Or were completely distracted by a momentous episode in your own life (e.g. mourning a loved one or giving birth)?

The Times is looking to compile the memories of Maltese people in a way that helps us sensitively mark this tragic episode which shaped the course of history.

Follow link below:
http://www.timesofmalta.com/sections/view/9-11-remembered

status_message:
Child Magazine and The Times TV Guide out tomorrow! 

Child - One of the most important developments in local education for the past few years was the launch of the draft curriculum framework a few days ago. When approved, it will establish the quality and direction of schooling for years to come.
Parents have been asked to provide feedback on the document and tomorrow, Child magazine, out free with The Times, offers a reader-friendly introduction to the ideas it contains. It is essential reading for all parents interested in their children's education.
More guidance abounds in the magazine, ranging from healthy nutrition to dealing with bullies, tips on internet research with children to some sound advice for mothers-to-be on Caesarian births. Overall it is yet another edition of Child, published by Allied Newspapers and produced by Mediamaker, that readers will want to keep for future reference.

TV Guide - Want to know what's happening on the local entertainment scene? And hear the latest about Sir Cliff Richard's recent visit to our island? And what the public's opinion on whether watching TV is a waste of time?
The Times TV Guide gives detailed and up-to-date programming information on over 60 local and foreign television channels throughout the coming week, including Melita and GO television cable channels. The guide also includes an exciting mix of features, interviews and gossip. And that's not all... in tomorrow's issue, you can also try your luck at winning an array of great prizes, including dinner for two at Il-Pjazza (Le Meridien St Julians), a 50 euro voucher from Diesel Kids, two cinema tickets courtesy of KRS Film Distributors, an exclusive Ferrari Scudetto mug and the beautiful coffee-table book 'At Home with the President'.
So make sure you pick up your copy of The Times TV Guide with your newspaper tomorrow.
The Times TV Guide is published by Allied Newspapers Ltd and distributed every Saturday with The Times.

status_message:
Ninety per cent of those afflicted with lupus, the as yet incurable chronic illness of the immune system, are women, 80 per cent are between the ages of 15 and 35 and about 180 are estimated to be suffering from the disease in Malta.
On the occasion of World Lupus Day, which was celebrated last week, Pink magazine's health section sheds light on the many faces of the illness – no two lupus patients present with similar symptoms and three women from various walks of life talk about how it has affected them individually.
Lupus is neither infectious, nor contagious, but patients prefer to hide it. Moreover, early diagnosis can make a major difference, which is why Pink tackles the subject and raises awareness in the May issue, out with The Times tomorrow.
Mother's Day, also celebrated this month, could not go by unnoticed in the women's magazine. But Pink has opted to pay tribute to the truly great grandmothers, who have dedicated themselves to taking care of their children's children so that they can continue with their lives.
The pros and cons of resorting to full-time nannies are also tackled in a story that focuses on those mothers who have no one to turn to in order to assist them in child care.
But it is not only mothers and children who feature in Pink. Women have other roles too and the magazine gets the rules of the game from Malta's top-class female referee as regards fielding the insults of the male fans at the stadium – but worse still, those of her own sex too. The article fires questions on whether football is as sexist sport and Esther Azzopardi calls the shots.
As always, fashion too plays a central role, with a sizzling bikini shoot and pages on accessories and trends, while beauty also makes it on to the cover with a sample of the new Scholl Hard Skin Softening cream for readers to try and test.

status_message:
Surviving the big C

A man's determination can be inspiring and life affirming, even when it is life itself that is at risk. Designer and art director Carlo Schembri is one determined man. When, just one week before his wedding, he was diagnosed with a rare form of cancer, he battled on through hours of interventions and rehabilitations to survive.
In M magazine, which is out tomorrow, Davinia Hamilton meets Mr Schembri to see what makes him a survivor.
Determination is also what fuels men who, having studied for and practised a particular profession, decide to make a leap straight out of their comfort zone. Sandy Calleja Portelli interviews two men who had the courage to change careers.
Men are stereotypically pictured as carnivorous hunters who relish the prospect of a juicy slab of red meat. Not all men, however, fit this portrait, as Velislava Hillman finds out when she meets two committed male vegetarians.
Love is more beautiful when played against a musical background – Veronica Stivala listens to the love story of musicians Jennifer Micallef and Wayne Marshall.
M also takes a look at Felix Busuttil's photo album, cooks up a seafood treat, and watches on as an Inter fan marries a Milanista wife.
M magazine will be out tomorrow with The Times. Published by Allied Newspapers Ltd, it's designed by MediaMaker Ltd and printed by Progress Press Ltd. Its editor is Stanley Borg.

status_message:
In Malta, only one couple with severe disabilities is married and lives independently. Husband and wife, both Muscular Dystrophy sufferers, with barely any mobility, want to serve as role models for others in similar situations and are proof that romance and disability are not incompatible.
The March issue of Pink, which is out with The Times tomorrow, discovers how couples with physical and intellectual disability manage to develop their intimate relationships and express their feelings of love, despite their limitations.
Not even their wheelchairs can keep them apart and they have accepted to share their matrimonial bed with respiratory machines, needing someone to place their hands on each other and having a hard time to kiss on their wedding day.
These and other lovebirds have chosen to open up about their right to a relationship and their emotional and sexual needs, which are no different from anyone else's.
International Women's Day has been done – and overdone – this month. But for Pink, which has always highlighted female issues, every edition marks it. Whether it is a woman's world is the burning question, especially in the aftermath of revolutionary uprisings, which are supposed to bring about change and freedom.
After the US-led invasion, Iraqi females are still being oppressed. They tell Pink they have lost their basic freedoms and are forced to cover up, fearing sexual violence that is keeping professionals in their homes and away from work.
Look out for a burst of floral fashion, loads of beauty tips from various angles and the usual regulars on food, fitness, psychology, books, cars, homes, history and humour.
Published by Allied Newspapers Ltd and printed by Progress Press, Pink is produced by Mediamaker. Its executive editor is Fiona Galea Debono and it is designed by Helen Cassar Torreggiani and Joseph Schembri.

Updated: Mosta fireworks factory explosion - One man dead, others missing
Share your pictures here

Updated: Mosta fireworks factory explosion - Rescuers looking for missing man
Photo: Mark Laferla JrRescuers are looking for a man who is reported missing in the 15 August Fireworks Factory explosion which rocked Malta at precisely 3 p.m. today, sending a big mushroom shaped cloud over the area.A number of ambulances were immediately rushed to the area.The explosion was heard practically across Malta, with readers reporting hearing it in Marsascala and Mellieha. Some said there had been three explosions, of which one was significantly bigger than the others.Mark Laferla, a reader from San Pawl tat-Targa, said it seemed like the burning wreckage landed in nearby fields and started multiple smaller fires.Doors and windows, he said, shook and it felt similar to an earthquake.The blast is the fourth involving a fireworks factory this year.Two people died in a blast at St Sebastian fireworks factory near Qormi in Febrruary and another man died in an explosion between Zejtun and Marsaxlokk in May but there were no injuries in an explosion at a Gharghur fireworks factory in April.
